Telecom Pandas Practical Case: Understanding fixed penetration trends in Colombia¶

  • Version: v1.0
  • Author: Juan David Rodriguez

Case Instructions¶

This case intends to evaluate and develop your capacity to use data and machine learning models in python to answer practical questions and assess business implications. Please read instructions carefully, each code block has a validation code, run each item sequentially to make sure that the validation code is valid in each step of the process. This case will allow you to:

  • Read and store in a DataFrame a compressed dataset
  • Clear and fix isues with outliers
  • Filter and aggregate data
  • Use basic python modules to visualize data
  • Prepare data to enter a machine learning model
  • Run a machine learning model (k-means clustering) using real data

Context and Background¶

This case uses real data from Colombia’s Telecom Industry, the objective is to understand the evolution of the fixed internet access in Colombia: As a developing country, Colombia has been trying to massify and improve penetration of the internet service. Most of the big cities have advanced telecommunications' offers, while small cities in rural areas have had limited internet access based on legacy technologies. Colombian government have developed a series of initiatives to improve fixed internet services in rural areas, aiming to improve digitalization.

Questions to answer:¶

  1. How is the evolution of the general penetration of fixed internet in Colombia? Are there specific trends that can be identified from the graph? Is the current penetration high or low? What is the maximum penetration that can be reached if it is measured as instructed in this question?
  2. Does the evolution of the penetration differ for big and small cities? Is the gap increasing or decreasing (take a clear position and support it with numbers resulting from your analysis)
  3. How does average internet offered speeds vary between big cities and small cities? Is the gap increasing or decreasing (take a clear position and support it with numbers resulting from your analysis)
  4. Is the distribution between internet service providers different in big cities and small cities? What are the pros and cons of using a pie chart to present this information?
  5. Previous questions have shown that two very different groups of cities can be separated by population (size of the city), Can cities be grouped or clustered based on other indicators in the dataset? What are the characteristics from each cluster?
  6. Liberty Latin America currently does not have a B2C (Business-to-Consumer) operation in Colombia. Based on the data provided in the case study, please provide a recommendation for the most effective entry strategy and identify specific groups of cities for its implementation.

Sources of data:¶

The Colombian government has enabled the website https://www.datos.gov.co/, where public data has been downloaded for internet access penetration, providers, type of technology and population for each city. A simple preparation was performed to reduce the size of the file and merge the different sources into one. The base resulting file is called 'Fix_Internet_Tech_City_Period.csv.gz'

Clearing and preparing data¶

There are three preparation tasks that shall be completed before continuing with the data:

  • Downspeed: Some of the registries are in Mbps and some in kbps. To correct this issue in the source data, registries above 1000 shall be divided by 1000. Replace existing downspeed column with the corrected values.
  • Quarter Key: All the analysis are made considering the quarter for a given year, in order to ease the aggregation and comparison, a quarter key including the year and the corresponding quarter shall be added.Insert a new column called 'YEAR_QUARTER'
  • Total Speed per registry: One of the most important KPIs that needs to be calculated is the average speed. However, the data has one row for each type of connection (technolog, vendor, speed), therefore, to avoid loosing information when aggregating data, I created the Total speed column which is the multiplication of the number of connections by the speed per connection . Insert a new column called 'TOTAL_SPEED'

Add/modify those columns over the original fixed_internet_base DataFrame

1. How is the evolution of the general penetration of fixed internet in Colombia? Are there specific trends that can be identified from the graph? Is the current penetration high or low? What is the maximum penetration that can be reached if it is measured as instructed in this question?¶

Follow the next steps to answer that question:

  • Group data using the function .groupby() by city and quarter, adding all internet connections for each city, and keeping the total population for each city
  • Group data by quarter adding all internet connections and city populations. Hint: City Population variables shows the total population from each city for all rows in a given quarter. ie: ALL rows from CITY_FULL_ID 11-11001 ("BOGOTA, D.C.") in quarter 2018-4 will show a CITY_POPULATION of 7412566
  • Calculate the national penetration per quarter by dividing the number of Internet Fixed Access by the total population

1.1 Group data by city and quarter, adding all internet connections for each city, and keeping the total population for each city. Store the result in a DataFrame called fixed_int_city_penetration

In [8]:
### Write your Core Here###
fixed_int_city_penetration = fixed_internet_base[['YEAR_QUARTER','CITY_FULL_ID','CITY','TOTAL_SPEED','CITY_POPULATION','NUMBER_INTERNET_CONECTIONS']].\
                            groupby(by=['YEAR_QUARTER','CITY_FULL_ID','CITY']).\
                            agg({'TOTAL_SPEED':'sum','CITY_POPULATION':'max','NUMBER_INTERNET_CONECTIONS':'sum'}).\
                            reset_index()

fixed_int_city_penetration['PENETRATION'] = fixed_int_city_penetration['NUMBER_INTERNET_CONECTIONS']/fixed_int_city_penetration['CITY_POPULATION']

print(fixed_int_city_penetration.iloc[4,3])

4. Is the distribution between internet service providers different in big cities and small cities? What are the possible implications of that difference?¶

Data has shown that there is a significant gap in penetration and offered speeds between small cities and big cities. This difference might be explained because the biggest internet providers might not be interested in serving small cities in rural areas, and hence the quality and coverage of the offer migth be inferior in small cities. Follow the next steps to complete de task:

4.1 Large cities:

  • Add the column 'CITY_CAT' to the original dataframe (fixed_internet_base) using the same method that you used to solve item 2.2 and the same separation threshold (threshold_pop) for large and small cities.
  • Create the DataFrame vendor_share_large_cities by filtering from fixed_internet_base the registries where fixed_internet_base['YEAR_QUARTER'] == '2021-3', and fixed_internet_base['CITY_CAT'] == 'large_city'. Include only the following columns: 'INTERNET_PROVIDER' and 'NUMBER_INTERNET_CONECTIONS'
  • Aggregate the resulting vendor_share_large_cities DataFrame by 'INTERNET_PROVIDER' using groupby() function. Store the result in the same vendor_share_large_cities. Sort values by the aggregated 'NUMBER_INTERNET_CONECTIONS' in descending order and reset index.
  • Select the 9 largest Internet Providers and group all other vendors in a row called "Others"
  • Calculate column vendor_share_large_cities['SHARE_LARGE_CITIES'] with the percentage participation or market share for each Internet Provider in Large cities.
  • Drop the column 'NUMBER_INTERNET_CONECTIONS'

Your resulting DataFrame shall have the following schema:

  • 'INTERNET_PROVIDER': Internet providers as provided in the original dataset
  • 'SHARE_LARGE_CITIES': % share of connections from each Internet Providers in Large Cities

Your DataFrame shall have 10 rows: 9 rows with the largest Internet Vendors for large cities and one row with the market share for the remaining providers called "Others".

5.4 Run the k-mean analysis Once the final city panel is available, two preparation tasks shall be completed:

  • Extract the data-columns that shall be included in the clustering analysis
  • Normalize data (city population is in millions, while penetration is a percentage) and convert to np.array

Once the data is ready in the np array, the k-means analysis can be run using vq.means

Finally, the clusters can be characterized by understanding the mean of the clustering variables and the relationship between variables can be plotted using seaborn pairplot.

In [45]:
# Run the code below to complete the clustering analyisis:

# Extract columns that shall be used for the clustering analysis:
df = fixed_int_city_panel.drop(columns=['CITY','CITY_FULL_ID'])
# Normalize values and convert to np.array
array_k_means = np.array((df-df.mean())/df.std())

# Define k and run k-means clustering
k = 4
centers_vq, distortion_vq = vq.kmeans(array_k_means, k)
clustering_vq, _ = vq.vq(array_k_means, centers_vq)

# Merge the cluster id to the city panel
fixed_int_city_panel['clustering_vq'] = clustering_vq

# Characterize clusters
cluster_characterization = fixed_int_city_panel[['CITY_FULL_ID','CITY_POPULATION','NUMBER_INTERNET_CONECTIONS','PENETRATION','AVG_SPEED','CABLE_%','FTTX_%','SATELITAL_%','COPPER_%','clustering_vq']]\
                            .groupby(['clustering_vq']).agg({'CITY_FULL_ID':'count','CITY_POPULATION':'mean','NUMBER_INTERNET_CONECTIONS':'mean','PENETRATION':'mean','AVG_SPEED':'mean','CABLE_%':'mean','FTTX_%': 'mean','SATELITAL_%':'mean', 'COPPER_%':'mean'})\
                            .sort_values(by='PENETRATION').reset_index()
